e problem with hearing the ones of others'.<br>
<br>
That being said, I don't think I ever expressed any anti-war sentiments Kadandrum. In my earlier post I questioned the motives of the war as presented by President Bush in his speech. Even though I wouldn't wish war even on Saddam, I'm cynical enough to accept that wars will happen. The point is, I think declaring them should be the job of the UN, not any single country. Saddam or Iraq itself is pretty insignificant, but when the most powerful nation in the world shows it doesn't care about international law, what kind of example will that be to other leaders of questionable reputation. You are half correct in that personally I oppose war because I don't like the US way of handling it. If it was approved by the UN, I wouldn't like it but neither would I have a problem with it. I still stand behind my points in my previous posts; US undermining UN is bad. Also, the US is wrong in refusing worldwide treaties for selfish gain. While I don't necessarily like US hegemony, it isn't a problem until it's abused. US is slowly edging on the abuse.<br>
<br>
Aybolit, my point was that the US has a military budget that is as big as the budgets of 14 runner-up countries combined. It runs a sizeable budget deficit yet it keeps increasing military spending, since wars aren't cheap. As you know, the Soviet Union crumbled since it's economy collapsed under military spending. Was just a sarcastic observation, if I was American I would be asking what's going on. I never implied Iraq would be the reason of this spending, actually I was wondering what is the US gearing up for.<br>
<br>
